- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/85/203785/2/check/gate-governance-docs/3a2a39a//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 55s'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-27 16:55:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@dean. So I think the question this is answering is "can I expect this to work with devstack", which is a thing that users ask quite often, as devstack works as an evaluation tool.

I would not expect a grenade plugin tag, that would be conceptually wrapped up in upstream upgrade testing.

OSC, I could see that being a thing.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-07-28 12:24:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

If you keep two tags, you'll need two separate files for the tagged-projects directive to work correctly. (that's why I codereviewed -1)

I was wondering if we should not regroup all "integration" tags under a single tag category, for example:
integration:devstack

or integration:devstack-plugin + integration:devstack-mainline if we want to keep the distinction.

That will let us have integration:horizon* integration:heat* etc. in the future.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-07-28 20:19:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(2 comments)

threw some possible aliasses up for your consideration'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-07-28 20:29:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I like the idea of just one tag expressing that a project works with devstack.  It doesn't seem necessary to me to be so granular as to document which mechanism is used.  So I'm generally more in favor of one tag for this.

If we do one tag, "integration:devstack" seems good to me too.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-07-28 21:43:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

+1000 in principle, but I'd prefer only one tag.

I think the argument behind having two tags is that it makes it clear to users that there are two different ways to install the plugins. I think this is a justifiable concern, and I think the best solution would be for devstack to ensure that there's only one way to install/activate a plugin, that's consistent across all projects. (If that means moving the in-tree plugins out-of-tree, I am more than fine with that - it makes it even more consistent.)

I'm not saying that the TC has to browbeat devstack maintainers into making that change, but I do think that codifying historical quirks of individual projects as permanent features of the community governance structure is almost always a mistake. At best it adds a lot of organisational inertia to what should be considered an implementation deal, and at worst it can be interpreted as an endorsement of the kind of two-tier system we were trying to get away from with tags.

Note that there are a bunch more tags along similar lines that we want to add (plugin support for e.g. Heat, Horizon, &c.), and this one is kind of the prototype for those. So it's nothing to do with devstack specifically, I believe that similar arguments apply in all of those cases.

I don't have any better ideas for names either. I agree that avoiding the word 'support' is very wise."}, {'account_id': 6783, 'date': '2015-07-30 13:10:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-12 11:59:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-21 12:31:54.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to formal-vote'}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-08-23 15:49:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-07 10:06:53.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I continue to believe that having the distinction is important from dealing with day to day issues in this space.

That seems to be a sticking point, so I think that instead of doing this as a tag, we'll just find the right way to do it in project documentation."}]

commit_message:
add devstack tags

This adds 2 tags devstack:upstream and devstack:has-plugin to document
the ways that projects might be runable in devstack.

I'm not thrilled on tag naming, please help come up with something
better. I want to avoid the use of the word "support" or "supported"
because I think that gives the wrong expectations. But english is
otherwise failing me.

Change-Id: Ie940a53e3b5c197801d7c9be2047f1ee35cd0da0

commit_message:
Do not reset locks on flush()

Deadlock detecter shouldn't clean locks list on flush(), because there
are only two cases when SQLAlchemy really resets locks:

* commit
* rollback

Currently, we have passed tests only because we use patched Query -
with '_populate_existing=True' which apparently causes flush() not
to be called before .all() calls and that's not a general behaviour.

Related-Bug: #1452359

Change-Id: I310cbc5e72b33af91e91264918665e4489f81a5c
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Change POST container semantics

To achieve last modified header on GETorHEAD container
we should allow POST container to overwrite put-timestamp.
That is because following patches will change the the put-timestamp
value semantics in both container db and account db as "container
last modified".

If we achieved this and followings, we will be able to retrieve the
container timestamp which is suggested when the container metadata
modified.

Example:
- Create a container.
- Change the ACL with POST container. (e.g. x-container-read)
- After that, we can know the container was changed by comparing
  between the timestamp from container creation and the last modified
  generated from put-timestamp.

Change-Id: I1a545fcd1896798dfa7cb5e5af97c78f5d7d7e4d

commit_message:
Removing /dev/log on rsyslog start

Currently we seem to be experiencing races between containers.
If another containers tries to write to rsyslog before rsyslog container
is up and running it will create /dev/log as directory,
and that will prevent rsyslog from starting.

Change-Id: I88ac27693d12e605f95e3a945fc98783516d7933
Closes-Bug: #1501694
backport: liberty

commit_message:
Install agent dependencies from source for CentOS

Several packages are not installed from RPM packages which are
required in order for CentOS from source to operate correctly.

This looked like sudo was failing to execute, but it was because
the dnsmasq binary was not found.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: If23cfbacd55d9089ffec442399ee0151adea923f
Closes-Bug: #1503412

Enable source for openstack-base for RPM distros

Make openstack-base optimized for from source builds for RPM based
distributions.

commit_message:
[ceilometer] update docs to reflect dependency of notification agent

update notification agent notes:
* the notification agent now handles all pipeline processing. polling agents
  send data to notification to be processed
** https://blueprints.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+spec/pollsters-no-transform
** https://review.openstack.org/#/c/198865/
* notification does not need direct connection to database
** https://blueprints.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+spec/notification-pipelines
** https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147704/

Change-Id: If2efb8d64b6fca288c9e21825e91657eecdf7d16

commit_message:
Avoid adding flood flow when l2pop is enabled
When ovs agent start, it should not add tunnel flood flow when l2pop is enabled, because later when port is up, plugin will instructs ovs agent to install the corresponding fdb entry
Fixes Bug1312257

Change-Id: I81e14bf586620b845928cd1cb3b764cedaf6dd55

commit_message:
Skip gate-neutronclient-dsvm-functional-adv-svcs prior to Liberty

It looks like support is only available in master [1] and that causes
stable fixes to fail CI [2,3].

[1] https://github.com/openstack/python-neutronclient/blob/master/tox.ini#L29
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/231736/
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224537/

Change-Id: I8549db52fa5b752202ac7f019b3e1931a697e337

commit_message:
Adds more functional tests for commands

This adds additional functional tests for the commands API.
It also restructures the current functional test to run in
sequence as a monolithic test to preserve IPA state and test
order between test runs. The time to wait for IPA to start
was increased due to an intermittent race condition that
occurs with the larger test suite.

Partial-Bug: 1492036
Change-Id: Iff9b41fb531d34225d702b9bfd39826e3c7195ad

commit_message:
Hide token id in logs

Until this time it was possible to steal token from the logs. Token
was logged during muranoclient creation.

SecurityImpact
Closes-Bug: #1503059
Change-Id: Ia2c7e19872a4d5b5093acd2e43b76273f02996e9

commit_message:
Update python-fuelclient rpm SPEC

Make python-fuelclient rpm spec closer to Packaging:Guidelines [1,2]

1. http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging:Python
2. https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging:Python_Eggs

Change-Id: Ib9195ecb01b7243b026001af423b4c9fdc4dde12
Closes-bug: #1451809

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V UEFI Secure Boot spec

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/hyper-v-uefi-secureboot

Secure Boot is a mechanism that starts the bootloader only if the
bootloader's signature has maintained integrity, assuring that only
approved components are allowed to run.
Secure Boot is dependent on UEFI.

Change-Id: I9b46307b9f747b1fb7a1f1cdfc34e272006fee42
Implements: blueprint hyper-v-uefi-secureboot

commit_message:
rabbit: always delete unused queues after a while

DONT MERGE, this doesn't allow upgrade

Some queues doesn't need to be auto_delete, but the side effect of that is
that deployer have to cleanup unused queues himself.

This change sets a expiration on queues when auto_delete is not set
to automate the cleanup. This can be configured by
rabbit_queues_default_expirations with a default of 12 hours.

Closes-bug: #1414674

Change-Id: I1fb8e9a6fb9a0fceb7a3f9c841906501548c3670

Seems like a nice idea:

Some thoughts...

What about using messages 'content/type' to specify this; assume the content-type is json unless overriden (or in the 2.0 version...), otherwise have a check for content-type json or msgpack and decode accordingly?

Here's something else; kombu afaik will already decode/encode from<->to msgpack (without using the oslo.utils helper); this could be useful (but I guess with the other non-kombu drivers in oslo.messaging it might not work);

From my understanding kombu uses:

https://github.com/celery/kombu/blob/master/kombu/message.py#L37 (content_type here); For some reason kombu thinks msgpack is insecure (idk why) but it can just be flipped on here:

https://github.com/celery/kombu/blob/master/kombu/serialization.py#L406

Note the default is json:

https://github.com/celery/kombu/blob/master/kombu/serialization.py#L390"}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-02-09 09:46:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Joshua Harlow: even we use the content type for the format, we need something to define the payload version, perhaps we will add an additional field in the future or somethings.

About the builtin kombu serialization, this can be only a kombu driver optimization. The specs only concern the common code path of all drivers. But I like the idea to remove the double encode/decoding that occurs on each message. Beside that, it seems that kombu allows to register custom serialization/deserialization method, so we can write one that use our common code and then skip the double step serialization/deserialization.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-09 16:29:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

PoC: Add new serialization format (3.0)

This change adds a new serialization format (3.0) that use
msgpack to serialize/deserialize message payload.

Implements blueprint msgpack-serialization

commit_message:
Centralize common imagecache options

In an attempt to provide more complete help strings for these config
options without disrupting the flow of the code in the module, move
these flags to a new file and then refer to them where used.

Change-Id: I6c36dce21a4f8be4e52e8cdfa3b1ae2b9c48fe48

Update for openstackdocstheme 1.2.3

Improve Manila HDS HNAS Driver Manual

Improve the network configuration guide for Manila HDS
HNAS Driver. Also, describe the driver modules following
other documentations.

commit_message:
Add coverage target to tox.ini

This creates a seperate target splitting out the coverage from the other
tests. The test directory and project names are different, overriding with
passed package name. Since testr is not used, coverage is called separately.

Change-Id: I32c132414a8b7e702b65617b95236397f4a471c2

commit_message:
Update for openstackdocstheme 1.2.3

Require new version and cleanup conf.py, we do no need pwd variable
anymore.

Sync pbr requirements with global requirements. Update
openstack-doc-tools requirements, we use 0.30 everywhere else.

commit_message:
Add puppet-openstack_spec_helper repo to Puppet OpenStack project

puppet-openstack_spec_helper will be a Gem library consummed by Puppet
OpenStack modules.

It will be first use to put common code used to configure beaker-rspec
but it could become later a common library used by our modules to
realize common tasks specific to OpenStack CI.

commit_message:
Add renderspec repo to Packaging-rpm governance

renderspec is a new tool that renders generic RPM .spec templates into
distribution specific .spec files to build packages from.

This way, we can share one package dist-git between different RPM
distributions.

Change-Id: Icacedc575c090ab1fdb8c8952e17328b146f32bb

commit_message:
Add 'suspended' lifecycle event

Hyper-V can emit events signaling that an instance was suspended.
The issue is that at the moment, there is no lifecycle event defined
for this instance state in nova.virt.event.

This patch adds this lifecycle event and ensures that the manager
will properly handle it.

Partially fixes bug: #1428505

Change-Id: I0fad28025785e77ef32b88ff813f39000d9f9e35
(cherry picked from commit 4720be6f29ab1c2479b9108c7d1565a6e765baef)

I don't think this is a right approach making all volumes shared by default.

This feature is setting the volumes as shared (between instances), however, this didn't mean to specify that this is a volume on shared storage.
I know that qemuMigrationDriveMirror skips "shared" volumes, but this is really targeting a different feature.

Defining the volumes as shared will remove the selinux isolation to the volumes and will allow access to it from any other instance, as well as it will disable the i/o caching.

I'm not yet sure what is the best approach here, however, I will look into this.

Maybe the best way to detach these volumes from the source and a attach on the destination.'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2014-11-05 09:30:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I don't think you can attach/detach volumes, otherwise you'll end up with service interruption, which you don't want when doing live migration.

If using the shared flag is not the right approach, maybe we need something else in libvirt to be able to skip those volumes? AKA a new flag?"}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2014-11-05 11:28:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-11-13 01:20:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Yes, I think something in libvirt is need to address this problem. However, I think, we will still need to attach on the destination side, to connect to the storage (iscsi, etc) and prepare the volume.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-14 15:43:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

Adding the <sharable/> flag is absolutely not what we want todo. By default libvirt assumes each disk is exclusively given to a single VM, and its lock manager will attempt to block starting of multiple guests with the same disk. The <shareable> flag tells libvirt that the disk is intended to be used by multiple VMs at the same time. This is absolutely not what Nova intends.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-14 15:45:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The root problem here is that we need a fine grained way to tell block migration which disks to copy and which to skip. This will require libvirt enhancement before we can do anything in Nova.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-01-23 15:23:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Make libvirt volumes shareable for block migration

This adds the shareable flags to all volumes attached to a libvirt
domain so that block migration skip their mirror operation during block
migration.

Co-Authored-By: florent.flament@cloudwatt.com
Change-Id: I3a33a1895cc0b38f18cde7978f67d8c710f50507
Closes-Bug: 1376615

commit_message:
Improved tests for hardcoded passwords

This replaces the existing hardcoded password test with a number of
smarter tests. None of the new tests utilize a word dictionary, we
now trigger the warnings based on matching variable names and the
like against a list of candidate names:

 - "password"
 - "pass"
 - "passwd"
 - "pwd"
 - "secret"
 - "token"

hardcoded_password_string looks for:
 candidate = "some_string_literal"
 dict[candidate] = "some_string_literal"
 candidate == "some_string_literal"

hardcoded_password_funcarg looks for:
 func_call(candidate="some_string_literal")

hardcoded_password_default looks for:
 def func_def(candidate="some_string_literal"):

All issues are reported as MEDIUM confidence, LOW severity

Closes-bug: #1502348
Closes-bug: #1502343
Closes-bug: #1432887

Change-Id: I36d97ee838a7f08234b759c352649721d07e8ab0

commit_message:
Do no net/subnet checks during validate

Currently validation fails if the network or the subnet are defined in
the same template as the server because they don't exist during
validate.

_validate_belonging_subnet_to_net is called during _build_nics so this
check still happens when the required resources actually exist.

Also, test method validate_internal_port_subnet_not_this_network was not
running because its name was not prefixed with test_. Fixing and
updating this test revealed issues with the validation failed message.

Closes-Bug: #1503060
Change-Id: I2e062abf5b9fb7446b979ba6acc2e2b531d957d6

[{'created': '2015-10-07 02:37:34.000000000', 'message': 'Correctly filter events on resource name

Filtering on resource name can be accomplished by using the db
filters instead of using a filter method. Furthermore, using a
custom filter breaks certain assumptions made by other parts of
the codebase, which lead to pagination being broken.
Specifically, custom filter for resource name is applied only
after other filtering is finished. As a result, we try to find
result from only 1 event and this event belongs to whole
stack and thus its resource_name is equal to the stack name.
This returns an event not found error instead of returning
the first event assosciated with the resource name.

Change-Id: Ie7d28ffb88a79d6e0f516f0db385be2eed59f7f0
Closes-Bug: #1502751
(cherry picked from commit 6322ff6fceabdfa226e5359328bde292d189e703)
'}]
commit_message:
Correctly filter events on resource name

Filtering on resource name can be accomplished by using the db
filters instead of using a filter method. Furthermore, using a
custom filter breaks certain assumptions made by other parts of
the codebase, which lead to pagination being broken.
Specifically, custom filter for resource name is applied only
after other filtering is finished. As a result, we try to find
result from only 1 event and this event belongs to whole
stack and thus its resource_name is equal to the stack name.
This returns an event not found error instead of returning
the first event assosciated with the resource name.

Change-Id: Ie7d28ffb88a79d6e0f516f0db385be2eed59f7f0
Closes-Bug: #1502751
(cherry picked from commit 6322ff6fceabdfa226e5359328bde292d189e703)

commit_message:
Re-add ZFSSA iSCSI cinder driver documentation.

This patch adds back the ZFSSA iSCSI driver documentation. It also adds
volume migration support documentation to the ZFSSA iSCSI as well as NFS
driver. Another change part of this patch is the addition of extra spec
documentation to the ZFSSA iSCSI driver.

Closes-Bug: 1501804
Closes-Bug: 1501806
Closes-Bug: 1503081

Change-Id: Ib682b6781695239e376378a637f8b0cab45ff3c4

commit_message:
Replace generate password for alternative in passlib

The passlib library which is in global-requirements already contains a
password generation utility function[1], so I added that one instead of
having our own implementation.

[1] http://pythonhosted.org/passlib/lib/passlib.utils.html#passlib.utils.generate_password

Change-Id: I2422f77cd77db03e1a8c3f95b1d5431bd95e5088

commit_message:
Fix few small issues with dockerctl inspect

* display inspect usage if no arguments were given
* iterate over given containers to show concatenated output
* print error message if one of many containers doesn't exist

Change-Id: Idfa3f3db01a5287d4970772b250f085ce890134e
Closes-bug: 1400776

commit_message:
Use inventory instead of hostfile parameter

The hostfile parameter in ansible.cfg is deprecated per documentation:
http://docs.ansible.com/ansible/intro_configuration.html#hostfile

This small patch update the hostfile parameter to inventory

Change-Id: I16a63c728d59799d70d2d1414aacf9a17eafcfb5

commit_message:
Enable Cisco N1KV driver

This enables support for the Cisco N1kv driver for the ML2 plugin.
It also configures the Nexus 1000v switch.

Co-Authored-By: Steven Hillman <sthillma@cisco.com>

Depends-On: I02dda0685c7df9013693db5eeacb2f47745d05b5
Depends-On: I3f14cdce9b9bf278aa9b107b2d313e1e82a20709

Change-Id: Idf23ed11a53509c00aa5fea4c87a515f42ad744f

commit_message:
Organized specs by release

The spec index page was getting very long with both the toctree depth
and no differentiation between releases. This change adds simple section
headers to separate the spec lists by release and decreases the depth of
the toc (very few third level sections offered any useful information).

Change-Id: I1c0aedc31010be825e4ad0b18540475f77b723db

commit_message:
Output strings in POT files in the order of file locaiton

Keeping the order of strings same as in the original source document
helps translators find the sources and they can translate by checking
rendered contents :-)

Note that Zanata keeps the order of strings in uploaded POT files.

Change-Id: I3ecd0516047050b94e8eba902620a4f40dc8fd36

commit_message:
Output strings in POT files in the order of file locaiton

Keeping the order of strings same as in the original source document
helps translators find the sources and they can translate by checking
rendered contents :-)

Note that Zanata keeps the order of strings in uploaded POT files.

Change-Id: I3ecd0516047050b94e8eba902620a4f40dc8fd36
Closes-Bug: #1503266

commit_message:
Move lib/apache to inc/apache

lib/apache is really more of a helper library, like other things in
inc/

As I9c8912a8fd596535589b207d7fc553b9d951d3fe shows, grenade is using
libraries like "lib/nova" with apache-function dependencies without
sourcing "lib/apache" (currently, the failures are hidden).

Move "lib/apache" into "inc/apache" and include it from "functions".
This ensures the apache-related functions are available everywhere you
would want them.

Change-Id: Ic84114bb833b74d346a9f2d8ca1832ce7d1fd7cd

commit_message:
Pin rabbitmq to 3.5.5

Pin rabbitmq to 3.5.5 for RPM platforms.  This version is the latest
and sparkly with lots of bug fixes.  Tested multi-node HA and everything
seems solid in comparison to the 3.3.z releases used previously.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I53bf70175fd12ded132141aa499c73919a932cdf
Closes-Bug: #1503280

commit_message:
Expand multinode network documentation.

Provide more info on why the mutlinode network setup exists as it does
today. This should provide better background on why certain choices were
made and general info on how it all works.

Change-Id: Ie04867a95f7e340dd3c1253aef0591bbf75bab8a

commit_message:
Fix for resource polling warnings

When neutron services are disabled,
neutron client logs the 404 exception
at warn level, this exception log
is unwanted and it suffices to log
just the error message.

Change-Id: I7ad8f43eacc9cfa9c66c424ab7ce3a05df5d2fa6
Closes-Bug: 1499403

commit_message:
VMAX Target iSCSI IP Address

In VMAX iSCSI driver, the iscsi_ip_address was hardcoded
in cinder.conf. This may have issues with multi-portgroup
environment. If a customer has multiple portgroups
containing different ports with different iSCSI IP addresses,
then â€˜iscsiadmâ€˜ command cannot use more than the one hardcoded
IP address in its sendtargets operation.

This patch addresses this by examining the ports in the
portgroup of the masking view used in the attach operation.
Each port has a corresponding iSCSI IP address. A portgroup
with only one port will have one IP address; a portgroup with
multiple ports will have multiple IP addresses. Even if there
is more than one IP address, the first in the list is likely to
result in a successful iscsiadm -sendtargets.

Closes-Bug: #1501678
Change-Id: I52ab6b278a114d55aec5e66b38ff76fd1bfb1b49

commit_message:
Keep py3.X compatibility for urllib

Use six.moves.urllib.parse instead of urllib.
For urllib2 compatibility, it need to sync policy
module from oslo first. Then six.moves.urllib.request
can replace urllib2.

Partial-Bug: #1280105

Change-Id: I1d4130731c0c506ed4b55ae4ca4b7157a5e8ea60

commit_message:
Delete orphaned instance files from compute nodes

While resizing/revert-resizing instance, if instance gets deleted
in between, then instance files remains either on the source or
destination compute node.

To address this issue, added a new periodic task
'_cleanup_incomplete_migrations' which takes care of deleting
instance files from source/destination compute nodes and then
mark migration record as failed so that it doesn't appear again
in the next periodic task run.

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/manager.py
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_mgr.py

SecurityImpact
Closes-Bug: 1392527
Change-Id: I9866d8e32e99b9f907921f4b226edf7b62bd83a7
(cherry picked from commit 18d6b5cc79973fc553daf7a92f22cce4dc0ca013)

commit_message:
Admin_state_up tempest test for health monitor

Use test scenario methods to do admin_state_up tempest test for health monitor.
Here are 3 methods:
1.test_create_health_monitor_with_scenarios
2.test_update_health_monitor_state_up_true_with_scenarios
3.test_update_health_monitor_state_up_false_with_scenarios

Added the base class as a dependency.

For each method, we need to test 16 secnarios, since we need to set admin_state_up
status for loadbalancer, listener, pool, health monitor, each has true and false status.
we setup the resources in the setup method, method validation is to check if the status
for admin_state_up is correctly setup or not.


Change-Id: I33b82ec550e7c876dbf2d0751054ff488b658e26

Fix wrong sysctl variable name

The bridge parameters should be net.bridge.* according to install
documentation at docs.openstack.org.

commit_message:
Do not log an error when deleting a linuxbridge does not exist

When you're racing to teardown and relying on RPC, it should not be
considered an error that a bridge does not exist when you're trying to
delete it anyway. This is better served as debug level information.

For context, this shows up over 1000 times in successful
gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-linuxbridge job runs in a week so it's
probably safe to say it's not contributing to test failures.

Closes-Bug: #1501779

Change-Id: I8e9b27e010d033291497f4e660a97bbae92e75b1
(cherry picked from commit a9dc48f5a4616a505824c3e8520c3dce7436f1b1)

commit_message:
Add ID column to compute service list

This change adds the ID to the compute service list command so that the
ID can be leveraged by scripts trying to remove or update a specific
service.

Change-Id: I446b4c0071988133195eb2382313b3918b7ffa72
Closes-Bug: #1503430

commit_message:
Download forbidden when get_image_location is set.

When using v2 an attempt to download an image would return a 403 if the
get_image_location policy was set.

Note: We had been returning both 404 and 204 when no data was
available. There was no way to detect the 404 case without trying to
access the image locations so I've standardized on 204.

Change-Id: I658b08a35d3a8cb8a7096baf716ccb3d6e7d9abf
Closes-bug: 1501672

commit_message:
Adds deactivated status for glance image

This patch adds the status deactivated for
images that have been deactivated in glance
thus also fixes the issue with progress bar
after image is deactivated.

Change-Id: I24c9fecb3cf67e1a2a56a0443e272a34a3585a74
Closes-bug: #1482094

The default bind_port (6011-6013) in the sample config files for swift
use port numbers that are in the range registered by X11 (6000-6063) and

'}]
commit_message:
Change the default bind_port for swift

The default bind_port (6011-6013) in the sample config files for swift
use port numbers that are in the range registered by X11 (6000-6063) and
can prevent swift from starting if the ports are in use.

We should use an unregistered range (6611-6613).

Change-Id: Ifd95b99004aead5ddc8ae1a8dd3ccd9c4f2abe91
Closes-Bug: #1254328

commit_message:
Add LimitRequestBody to sample httpd config

Web servers that are exposed to the Internet eventually gain a
security feature of limiting the amount of data in the request
body. In Apache Httpd, this is provided by the LimitRequestBody
directive. This is added to the sample Httpd config file.

The limit is set for only the keystone services so it won't
affect other services running in Httpd.

The value of 114688 was picked because it's the current limit
on request body that oslo.middleware's sizelimit function puts
on requests to keystone.

Use of oslo.middleware's sizelimit re-implementation can be
deprecated.

Docs:
- http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/core.html#limitrequestbody

ReleaseNotesImpact

Closes-Bug: 1481048
Change-Id: I5509e4b65900c15dd0b5fda43b1d5bb4dc3ff5ff

commit_message:
Fix for LDAP filter on group search by name

This fixes an invalid LDAP filter constructed by Keystone on v3 group
show command (i.e. search group by name). Similar to bug
https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1454309 but relates to groups.

Change-Id: Iae5d539cd0dc032b6126c50a6ba4c8100254edd5
Closes-Bug: 1468000
(cherry picked from commit ef37e2748d117ded3fa7279496f468fd65daf40c)

commit_message:
Update the devstack readme.md for Octavia as ref

The readme.md in the devstack directory did not get updated
for Octavia being the reference driver.  This patch updates
the document to enable the Octavia plugin.

Closes-Bug: #1500656
Change-Id: I39f9f9d060512c9b3af9dd08c413931f9b94cf78
(cherry picked from commit 872b8a5446726acb6483329724a500abb582cdf6)

commit_message:
Port netapp SSC Cmode to Python 3

Fix query_cluster_vols_for_ssc(): cast string (records) to int. On
Python 3, comparison between str and int now raise a TypeError.

commit_message:
Removed full path from conf file reference

In the original text, the full path was shown, which was incorrect for some
distros. Patch 231028 gave distro-specific paths, but we do not give
distro-specific information in this guide, and that patch has been reverted.
This patch fixes the original text to remove the full path, and replace it
with the name of the config file only.

Change-Id: I65726323ca15e53dc8d25a4e93627dfc6005cb46
Closes-bug: #1502927

commit_message:
Large Containers - container sharding spec

This is a new version of the container sharding spec. This time
it focuses entirely on the Distributed Prefix Tree (trie) version.

I will coninue tweaking the code in the POC as such there may
be a few more patchsets of this spec before the summit.

Change-Id: Ibf1cadb3649d501b6c371e03b1451d754fc4987c

Matt,

I am still reading through the spec. Sorry if those are duplicated questions. 

I am trying to understand the locking mechanism behind this algorithm  when multiple requests are traverse the tree. It will be interesting to see how the locking is played here when you have to insert or delete a node while other threads are traverse the tree(If this case is valid). I am trying to imagine this from file system incore inode 
management perspective. Please correct me if I am wrong.  

I assume the CountingTrie is an in-memory structure. How do we keep in sync with the on disk structure(again if this is a valid assumption) I assume the on disk part just need a one level directory to keep all the shards, am I right?

Is this algorithm every need to move the tree node from one shard to another shard? 

Another question, just for my education, why this is important?
"A determining factor in what sharding technique we chose was that having a consistent order is"

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-08-04 02:24:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hey Alan,

thanks for the questions.

> I am trying to understand the locking mechanism behind this algorithm when
> multiple requests are traverse the tree. It will be interesting to see how the
> locking is played here when you have to insert or delete a node while other
> threads are traverse the tree(If this case is valid). I am trying to imagine
> this from file system incore inode management perspective. Please correct me if
> I am wrong.

When multiple requests traverse which tree. The only class using the CountingTrie is the sharder and not via requests, so I assume you mean the ShardingTrie. In general, a request will come into the proxy, the proxy will ask the container-server(s) for the trie for the container in question (root or shard) at whatever state the trie is in when the proxy request hits the container-server. The request in the proxy will recieve the trie, and then do what it needs to do.
So multiple requests wont read the same in memory trie in the proxy. The Container-server will generate a trie from the current state of the sqlite database, and to grab the current list of objects would involve a lock.

Different types of requests use the trie differently:

  object PUT/DELETE:

    This gets a trie from the root container only, containing only the distributed nodes, as this request only needs to determine what shard container needs to be updated. This doesn't change every often and the number of distributed nodes and a couple of magnitudes smaller then a list of objects.

  container GET/HEAD

    The HEAD case all we need is a list of distributed nodes to query to get all the object counts, etc. The GET will build a full trie* which will be iterated over grabbing more tries to iterate as distributed nodes are hit.
There is a caveat however, we only grab CONTAINER_LISTING_SIZE (10k by default) size tries so this doesn't get too large. NOTE: limit, marker, end_markers are supported in sharded containers.

  container DELETE:

    Is much like the rest, all we need is the distributed nodes in a trie to now where to fire DELETE requests off to. Updating the root and parents dist node table as we go in case we find a container non-empty in which case the delete fails, but the sharded container is left in a correct state. NOTE: the sharder will collapse empty containers (shrinking), so there might not be as many shards to clean up.

So as you can see, in most cases we never need to build a large trie (in relation to size) and dist_nodes change much less.

> I assume the CountingTrie is an in-memory structure. How do we keep in sync
> with the on disk structure(again if this is a valid assumption) I assume the on
> disk part just need a one level directory to keep all the shards, am I right?
> Is this algorithm every need to move the tree node from one shard to another
> shard?

Yes it's in memory and only used by the container-sharder, to find candidate subtries for splitting and finding misplaced items to correct. Again it only does it at the current state of the database file, if an object is added between building the trie and splitting then this will be corrected by the sharder during the next run as a misplaced item, this behaviour I think is fine as swift is an eventually consistent system.

> Another question, just for my education, why this is important? "A determining
> factor in what sharding technique we chose was that having a consistent order
> is"

Swift if highly customisable, many deployments out there can extend swift via middleware. Some of the current middleware shipped with swift (dlo for example) to work correctly require the objects to be returned in the correct order. The prefix tree (trie) will maintain the order now matter where or how many times we shard, making sharding large containers transparent to external users.

If I need to make this more clear in the spec then
let me know :)

I have been working on some simplified sequence diagrams that may help, maybe I'll add them as images to my next iteration of the SPEC.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-08-04 02:24:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Update sharding spec, notably CountingTrie and shrinking

Updates to the sharding spec:
 - Root container short circuting
 - CoutingTrie and changes to finding suitable candidates and misplaced
   items.
 - Shard container auditing
 - Shrinking (collapsing) sharded containers (V1).

Change-Id: I5be0cfa240455a831d472e00c811c5e103bf60d3

Make client wrapper support create and delete operation so we
can create and delete aggregate in top OpenStack layer via DAL.

package and fix minor RST issue with code-block type.

commit_message:
[install] Load demo-openrc.sh again

Prior to gathering information for launching an instance,
we should load the demo-openrc.sh file again to put the
environment in a known state.

Change-Id: I2bb36a4014fe934c30dbd43f2e07539d337fa3ce
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty

Python 3.

commit_message:
Refactor list_all_block_devices & add block_type param

Put the columns to retrieve from lsblk into a list so that future
modifications to columns will require fewer code changes.

Also add a 'block_type' parameter which defaults to 'disk'. To make the
function more flexible if callers wanted a different block type.

Update and add unit tests

Change-Id: If06460e13a5b56dc8d6efca9ff5b58ac6ba1f357

[{'created': '2015-06-11 01:33:50.000000000', 'message': 'Add CRUD methods for Keystone roles

A user might list or get a role, because they will grant a role to users

commit_message:
Add CRUD methods for Keystone roles

A user might list or get a role, because they will grant a role to users
or projects they create in their domain. However, a cloud admin is the
one who creates roles.

Co-Authored-By: Haneef Ali <haneef.ali@hp.com>

commit_message:
ASG scaling account for cooldown timestamp & in-progress

There are cases where it takes a long time to create a new resource as
requested by the scaling operation on an ASG resource, for instance, a
nova server creation followed by a complex SoftwareDeployment. During
this process, additional alarms may come in but failed to be blocked
by the current cooldown checking mechanism because the very first
timestamp has yet to be generated. This is leading to unexpected size
adjustment to the ASG.

This patch augments the existing cooldown checking mechanism with a
scaling-in-progress test so that additional alarms arriving during
the very first scaling operation will be ignored.

Change-Id: I93eae99baa4a33ad0b1d34a6eb0aacb2ac5ddfa3
Closes-Bug: #1375156

commit_message:
Fix translating for props with get_param value

If some map or list type properties specified with
json-type or commadelimitedlist parameters, error
raised in case of wrong properties data parsing.
Fix this case by adding check if data is GetParam
instance, resolve it. Other function can be safely
replaced without resolve.

Change-Id: I0c9a6af29b56b629cbdad2acb868c3033e38b5ef
Closes-bug: #1494364
(cherry picked from commit aea59ecdac6ed6635125eb2064554140e3e645fc)

commit_message:
Provide option to delete floating IP with server

Although the only real reason you should need a floating IP are for
the cases where you want an IP with a lifespan independent from the
server, there are clouds that are insane and require a floating IP
to be created with every server. When a person is deleting that
server, we should ensure that the floating IP is delete. However, it's
impossible to infer intent about whether the floating IP wants to stick
around, so it has to be a flag.

We will default to False because deleting things that the user did not
expect to be deleted is surprising in a bad way.

Change-Id: Id90bdc819ad8f1b04acc1b35788786d23f4e7666

commit_message:
Rename 'message' attribute to '_msg_fmt' in IronicException

The 'message' attribute for exceptions has been deprecated since Python
2.6 and does not exist in Python 3. The IronicException 'message'
attribute will still exist (but should not be used) in Python 2.x as the
BaseException class provides it, but in Python 3.x it will no longer
exist.

The preferred way to get a message from an exception is
six.text_type(exc) as this provides the unicode version of the
exception.

This change renames the 'message' attribute to '_msg_fmt' to indicate to
users that they should not use it directly.

For any third-party users of the IronicException class, log a warning
that usage of the 'message' attribute is deprecated, but allow them to
keep working.

This is similar, but different, to work done in Nova:
  commit 70569ae344bceb3794713abc5cb2c82e9671c37d
  Author: Mark McLoughlin <markmc@redhat.com>
  Date:   Mon Jul 1 11:31:06 2013 +0100
  Subject: Avoid shadowing Exception 'message' attribute

Change-Id: Id080ea42d7ae6337ce23c1411cf4e8a903223d3d

Another reason for having specs is we have an artifact for looking back on a given feature and the context around the time it was proposed.  I think priorities are useful for that, but agree that we're in this weird limbo state right now where priorities aren't finalized until the summit but John wants a lot of specs reviewed (and hopefully approved) before the summit.  So I've been seeing people say 'priorities aren't yet determined for this release' in this section, which I think is OK.  I think in a lot of cases we could know that a spec is so specific to something that it's not a priority (some toggle thing in a single virt driver for example).

I'd be in favor of updating the wording in the template that basically says:

1. If you can reasonably assume that your spec is not a priority for the project for the target release, leave this entry as "None".

2. If priorities are not yet defined for the target release, leave a comment saying "The priorities for release <name> are not yet defined."

--

Having said that, I don't have a super strong opinion either way.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:43:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Its really tracked in launchpad in the blueprint priority anyways, along side the etherpad.

We may need to update the tests to make that work, I am bit surprised the template didn't fail here, but we can do that as a follow up.

If we want to keep this info in the specs repo, we can add a list of links to specs in the priorities page, thats probably a better way to handle this."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:59:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
template: remove "Project priority" section of spec

The "Project priority" section in the spec template is a source
of persistent confusion and mis-use. A large portion of spec
authors believe that it is a section to fill with their own
opinions on why their spec is important. In fact, pretty much
all specs should put the words "None" in this section. This is
particularly true earlier in the cycle, since the actual project
priorities do not get finalized / agreed on until the design
summit. Even once the priorities are agreed, this section of
the spec is still fairly pointless, since we've moved to tracking
priority specs in a separate etherpad. eg

  https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-nova-priorities-tracking

Just remove this source of confusion since it doesn't serve any
particularly useful purpose anymore, given the external tracking
done.

Change-Id: I808227fe71210abc64270f53ef3d3d62f176ff24

commit_message:
Replace .iteritems() with .items()

As mentioned in the developer's guide[0] and in a discussion[1], we
shouldn't use six.iteritems() unless there's a good reason (eg large
data set).

Since there's no need to use six.iteritems() or dict.iteritems() in the
two places where it is being used, this patch replaces them with
items().

[0] http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#peer-review
[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

Change-Id: Iaf4ffc755293454a054fff3efffd5a30e1c18fd7

commit_message:
Organise doc links for Operating Heat

The second section of doc links is aimed at operators, so existing
content which affects operators has been moved here (package based
install, scaling, service man pages).

The yum/apt install pages have been simplified to point at
docs.openstack.org and any other community based installation resources
(RDO, Juju charms).

Change-Id: I3e89a288bf6b64ba286c11df1369e073d2c2a35e

commit_message:
Correctly filter events on resource name

Filtering on resource name can be accomplished by using the db
filters instead of using a filter method. Furthermore, using a
custom filter breaks certain assumptions made by other parts of
the codebase, which lead to pagination being broken.
Specifically, custom filter for resource name is applied only
after other filtering is finished. As a result, we try to find
result from only 1 event and this event belongs to whole
stack and thus its resource_name is equal to the stack name.
This returns an event not found error instead of returning
the first event assosciated with the resource name.

Change-Id: Ie7d28ffb88a79d6e0f516f0db385be2eed59f7f0
Closes-Bug: #1502751

commit_message:
Do no net/subnet checks during validate

Currently validation fails if the network or the subnet are defined in
the same template as the server because they don't exist during
validate.

_validate_belonging_subnet_to_net is called during _build_nics so this
check still happens when the required resources actually exist.

Also, test method validate_internal_port_subnet_not_this_network was not
running because its name was not prefixed with test_. Fixing and
updating this test revealed issues with the validation failed message.

Closes-Bug: #1503060
Change-Id: I2e062abf5b9fb7446b979ba6acc2e2b531d957d6

commit_message:
Fix tempest-account-generator command roles issue

The change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/216109 modified the
identity client to return the entire response object instead of
only part of it. This patch fixes a call to list_roles that was
missed in the tempest-account-generator tool.

Change-Id: I0986dac6f8a37879f98583f2e1c899670970b668

commit_message:
Fix log formatting issue in agent base

This fixes a TypeError that would occur when trying
to provision an instance with local boot via IPA.

Change-Id: Ib9af83a831be5c5f344f0745e9b15d4a59ac5dac
Closes-bug: #1503008

commit_message:
remove additional service checks for upgrading

Even though you've told grenade to UPGRADE a project, we still go and
check to see if it's enabled in devstack before we believe you. For
components that are fully implemented in the grenade and devstack
trees, this is fine. However for plugins this is weird, because
stackrc doesn't provide enough information to figure this out.

We should not do this second check, just trust your grenade config is
correct. This code was probably vestigial to getting the refactor
working correctly before the kilo release.

Change-Id: I01d00f95d602b9b159b3b64ff46a7cd3e23c3983

commit_message:
Allow updating TLS refs

A bug prevented updating of default_tls_container_ref and failing
with a 503

This bug uncovered a few other issues with null key checks
and complaints if sni_container_refs were not provided.

Change-Id: I636e9f78b38ba9f02d10a013bf56459cc2a723e1
Closes-Bug: #1501505
(cherry picked from commit b8c3978de696786615cd72f90c0858d1032d241b)

commit_message:
Include nested stacks in reset_stack_status

Previously this applied only to top-level stacks.

Change-Id: I958dbbbecf91c1f86c52e90320a07c4a43e54551
Closes-Bug: #1501828

commit_message:
Add tags to `image set`

This adds --tag to the v2 version of `image set`. This
is another step to compatability between the osc image api.

Added merge of tags into existing tags and handling duplicates,
and tests for same.

Co-Authored-By: Steve Martinelli <stevemar@ca.ibm.com>

Change-Id: Ie800fcbf8bbc0978c54ace3278750a18023e8ce4

commit_message:
Ceph Object Gateway Temp URL support for Ironic

Ceph Object Gateway (RADOS Gateway) Temp URL has a different format
than OpenStack Swift. This spec proposes to support this format.

Change-Id: I9ef6ccf7c22c26c894f42a69b2893108ee7869a1

commit_message:
Ensure to decode bytes or fail

The commit fcf289797c063088f9003359dfd1c7d4f41ed5ef introduces the
pattern:

  if isinstance(line, bytes):
    try:
      line = line.decode(encoding='utf-8')
    except UnicodeError:
      pass
  # concat line with a string

which is not working in PY3K if an UnicodeError is raised because line
is not decoded and concatened to a string.

This change delegates decoding to safe_decode[1] which returns a text
object or raises an error.

[1] oslo_utils.encodeutils

Closes-Bug: #1503415
Related-Bug: #1499004
Change-Id: I16b8013f33aa3efad65be8040d3210120e047bbd

commit_message:
Let devstack-gate handle the gate hook timeout

Devstack gate now handles all of the hook timeouts itself so that
individual jobs do not need to reinvent this wheel. Remove the timeout
support from the functional test gate hook here as a result.

Change-Id: I3819978b04faea5712c995cbe277ae42870acba9

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Fix incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected) as below.
  assertEqual(observed, expected) => assertEqual(expected, observed)

Target of this patch:
  manila/tests/cmd/*
  manila/tests/compute/*
  manila/db/*
  manila/network/*

Change-Id: I6dd4f8057facc68e716b57229cbc4096af8bb152
Partial-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Bring Kolla inline with FHS

This brings Kolla images inline with FHS and should make finding
locations of things more consistent and reliable with the linux world
at large.

Change-Id: Iece5b4da4bace0fb8b1f41a65ab2c852ec73e6f8
Closes-Bug: #1485742
(cherry picked from commit 94162bd08f40ec742a7bfcdcd4aac45be5bd5618)

commit_message:
Common start.sh

The majority of the start.sh code is identical. This removes that
duplicate code while still maintaining the ability to call code in a
specific container.

The start.sh is moved into /usr/local/bin/kolla_start in the container

The extend_start.sh script is called by the kolla_start script at the
location /usr/local/bin/kolla_extend_start . It always exists because
we create a noop kolla_extend_start in the base directory. We override
it with extend_start.sh in a specific image should we need to.

Of note, the neutron-agents container is exempt from this new
structure due to it being a fat container.

Additionally, we fix the inconsistent permissions throughout. 644 for
repo files and the scripts are set to 755 via a Docker RUN command to
ensure someones local perm change won't break upstream containers.

Change-Id: I7da8d19965463ad30ee522a71183e3f092e0d6ad
Closes-Bug: #1501295
(cherry picked from commit cb4e875ae1e1ec2e6ddf8a6b37f42283697fd50c)

commit_message:
Set up stable/liberty branch

Update default branch in .gitreview and remove the version setting from
setup.cfg to make pbr understand that it can use post-versioning on the
branch.

commit_message:
verification: set timeout for requests.get when testing for Horizon

The default timeout for requests.get is None. Because of that the
requests.get call will hang forever if no Horizion dashboard is
available.

Change-Id: Ibbe7ff1ada234b6b733be2c29c278f0f0711219d
Closes-bug: #1501696
